Introduction
In the previous quest, you learned about Circle Payouts API, creating a bank account and sending a payout. In this quest, we will be exploring the Circle Accounts APIs by sending funds from one wallet to another. We will also go through the supported chain and currencies supported in Circle, and how Circle accounts and master wallet work.
For queries on this quest,  join our Discord, head to the #circle-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe the concept of addresses and digital wallets in the blockchain world
  • Send funds from one wallet to another wallet using Circle Accounts API
  • Identify supported chains and currencies of Circle API
  • Recognise the functions of the Circle account and master wallet

Deliverable
To successfully complete this quest, you will need to do the following: 
  1. Screenshot of a wallet transfer with a complete status. See Step 6 for more details.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Digital Wallets and Addresses
What are digital wallets? Digital wallets, also known as electronic wallets (e-wallets), are software, electronic devices or online services that allow individuals to make payments electronically without the actual need of possessing a physical wallet. It requires users to download the digital wallet app on their smartphones or other physical devices in order to access or make transactions. 
The most common examples are Paypal, Apple Pay, Google Pay and Venmo. Payment information of the user is usually stored on a website or mobile app along with other data like gift rewards. To make a payment with a digital wallet, the user simply has to authorize the digital wallet and hold it close to a card reader so that your information can be transmitted. 

An increasing number of people are using digital wallets due to the convenience of not needing to carry around a physical wallet and use it as a backup to make payments if a user forgets to bring their wallet out. Digital wallets also have better security mechanisms put in place as compared to physical debit or credit cards. Digital wallets usually have fingerprint scans, facial recognition or password protection as a layer of protection, whereas physical cards can easily be used by anyone if stolen.

Next, we will move on to the wallet address. A wallet address in the blockchain world is an identifier used so that a wallet can receive cryptocurrency funds. It is typically a string of alphanumeric characters, such as 0x8381470ED67C3802402dbbFa0058E8871F017A6F.

Different blockchains might have different wallet address formats. For technical reasons, it may not be possible to receive all tokens that exist on a given blockchain using the same address. This is why we had to create a blockchain address associated with our own master wallet identifier in order to receive USDC funds from another chain in the fifth quest.
Step 2: Creating a Second Wallet
We will use the Circle Accounts API to transfer funds from one wallet to another wallet. In Circle, a wallet transfer operation can happen in three ways:
  1. Transfer funds from an external blockchain address to a Circle-hosted wallet
  2. Transfer funds between two Circle-hosted wallets
  3. Transfer funds from a Circle-hosted wallet to an external blockchain address

We will use Circle Accounts API to transfer funds between two Circle-hosted wallets. However, we will first create another Circle-hosted wallet so that we can transfer funds from the master wallet to the newly created wallet.

Open up the Postman application and go to the Accounts API collection that was forked earlier in the fifth quest. Click on Create a wallet.



In the Authorization tab, set the type to Bearer Token and ensure your API key is correctly input. Next, click on Body Tab.



Generate a UUID for the idempotencyKey value. The value for description can be changed to your own preference, but we will call it 'Treasury Wallet' in our case.

After replacing the values, click the 'Send' button. You will see a response similar to what you see in 'expected output'.

Do take note of your walletId, which will be needed as the wallet destination to send funds to.
Expected output
Step 3: Transferring Funds Between Two Circle-Hosted Wallets
In your Postman interface, under the Accounts API, select the Transfers directory and click on create a transfer.
In the authorization tab, change the type to 'Bearer Token and make sure your API key is input into the token field. Now click on the Body tab. The current body JSON data contains data needed for transferring USDC from a wallet to an external blockchain address. Instead, lets change it to transfer between 2 Circle hosted wallets. The JSON data below is needed to transfer between our master wallet to the newly created wallet. You will need to make four changes in the body JSON.

{  "idempotencyKey": "{{$guid}}",  "source": {   "type": "wallet",   "id": "CHANGE TO MASTER WALLET ID"  },  "destination": {   "type": "wallet",   "id": "CHANGE TO NEWLY CREATED WALLET"  },  "amount": {   "amount": "AMOUNT OF YOUR CHOICE",   "currency": "USD"  } }

Generate a new UUID for the idempotencyKey value. Change the value for the id in the source object to your master wallet id. Then, change the id in the destination object to the wallet id you obtained in the previous step. The amount can be set to the amount of your choice. 

The final JSON data in the Body tab should look like this. 



Now, click the 'Send' button. The following output will be shown, with the status stated as 'pending'. 



It will take some time for the transaction to be fully completed. Wait for around 5 secs and click send again. The response should be updated to complete with the same idempotency key used. Your response should look similar to the 'expected output'.

Important: At this point, take a full screenshot of your Postman interface showing your successful API response. You will need this for your submission later.
Expected output
Step 4: Circle Supported Chain and Currencies
Circle Accounts API is designed for multi-chain and multi-currency support. A chain normally hosts one or more cryptocurrencies.
You may refer to this link to learn more about the chains and currencies currently supported by the Accounts API.
Step 5: Circle Account and Master Wallet
Earlier in the third quest, we created our Circle sandbox account to obtain the API key. For this campaign, we are only using the Circle sandbox environment with our sandbox account we created for testing and development purposes. However, for commercial usage by institutions, there is the Circle Account and Services which are available in supported jurisdictions. Also, you will need to sign up for a Circle account and contact the Circles sales team. 
A master wallet is automatically created when a user signs up for a Circle account. The master wallet is the destination for the settlement of payments and the origin for payouts when a user uses the Payments or Payouts Circle APIs. Each master wallet has an identifier which can be obtained from the configuration API endpoint used in Quest 5 Step 4.

Your masterWalletId value will always remain the same, so you can either store it or retrieve it via the configuration endpoint.
